Pre­Columbian Maya Graffiti: Context, Dating, andFunction. JAROSLAW ZRALKA. 2014. JagiellonianUniversity,Kraków.357pages,85plates.$18.10(paper),ISBN 978-83-64449-16-1. 
Reviewed by TraciArdren, University of Miami 
ThefascinatingtopicofClassicMayagraffitiisthesub-jectofanexhaustivenewpublicationbyJaroslawZralka.Based on 15 years of research compiling examples ofgraffitifromacrosstheMayaLowlands,Zralkahaspro-duced a long overdue summary of what is known (andwhatremainsfrustratinglyunknown)aboutancientMayagraffiti. The volume is centered on a description andanalysis of his catalog of more than 3,000 individualexamplesofgraffiticompiledfrompublishedandunpub-lished sources. Many of these come from the site ofNakum, in the Petén, Guatemala, where the author andcolleaguesfromJagiellonianUniversityhaveconductedfieldwork over the past 10 years. While the volume isprimarily descriptive, it provides a useful comparativeperspective that places Classic Maya graffiti within abroader global perspective. More seriously viewed as atopicsuitableforacademicstudybythefieldsofClassicsand Egyptology, the author draws upon this broader lit-erature base for useful and illuminating parallels. Pre­Columbian Maya Graffiti is richly illustrated with a setof 85 plates, most of which are good quality black andwhiteillustrationsoftheimagery,aswellasmanycolorphotographs throughout the entire publication.
The current volume builds upon earlier publicationsby the author on Maya graffiti at Nakum. To contextu-alizethenewNakummaterials,theauthorspenttimeinthe archives of the Tikal Project at the University ofPennsylvaniaMuseum.Finally,thecatalogwassupple-mentedwithfurtherexamplesfromsiteswithlessexten-sive records of graffiti. Zralka acknowledges that manyprojects did not record graffiti in the early days of ourdiscipline,anditisnotclearwhetherallresearchprojectsdosotoday.Theissueofsamplingistheresultofalonghistoryofthedismissalofgraffitiasasourceofvaluabledata on ancient life. The author chronicles, in painfuldetail, how many early scholars refused to see the use-fulness of graffiti and described the makers of this par-ticularartformasessentiallyhooligans.Oneofthemostimportant contributions of Zralka s volume is his docu-mentationthatthemajorityofgraffitiweremadeduringthe height of Classic civilization, likely during the LateandTerminalClassicperiods.Furthermore,hehasstrongargumentsforwhythemajorityofgraffitiwereprobablymade by members of the elite, or at least those familiarwith courtly life and spaces. For both of these reasonsalone,thisisasourceofdatathatMesoamericanistscanno longer afford to marginalize.
Pre­Columbian Maya Graffiti begins with a chapteron the history of the word graffiti and its evolution ofmeaning. Used in the eighteenth century to describeinscriptions at Pompeii, it wasn t until the nineteenthcenturythatittookonitscontemporarymeaningofillicitorunsanctionedartisticexpression.Afterexplainingwhythereisnoscholarlyconsensusonadefinitionforancientgraffiti, given the broad array of symbolic data that canbeconsideredgraffitiinvariousancientcultures,ZralkasettlesonadefinitionfortheMayaareathatincludes allrepresentations that are on buildings but do not pertainto their original design or context and which are furthercharacterized by low artistic quality (p. 39). This defi-nitionisnotentirelysatisfactory,eventoZralka,aslaterinthevolumehediscussesagroupofgraffitithat,giventheskillwithwhichtheyrepresentthehumanform,werelikely made by artists with the same level of expertiseand training as those who painted ceramic vases. Themajorityofexamplesofgraffiti,however,donotexhibitthis same skill, and while the term crude is rarelyappropriate in discussing the art of another culture, inthis case they are indeed a crude approximation of thefinerexamples,asZralkasuggests.Thenextchapterpre-sents comparativedata on whatkinds ofgraffiti existinother ancient cultures, such as Egypt or Rome, but alsoonhowgraffitihavebeenstudied.Mostofthesegraffitiare textual, and Zralka makes important points aboutthe authors of these inscriptions hardly being marginal-izedmembersofsociety.Chapter3presentsahistoryofresearch on Maya graffiti, which began when Stephensand Catherwood noticed red hand prints on the walls ofsiteslikeKabah.Animportantcontributortothecorpus 

