Thefinaltwochaptersmovebeyonddescriptionintomuch needed analysis and interpretation. First, Zralkadiscussesthe14majorthemesheidentified anthropo-morphicimagesaremostcommonbyfar(43.6percent),anddepictionsoffamiliarMayathemessuchashighsta-tus individuals, warriors, musicians, and captives arepart of this theme. The remaining 66 percent of imagesareextremelyvaried,someareabstractandgeometrical,others are more representational, such as animals andpatolli game boards. The author does a good job ofexplaining these themes and why individual images areplaced within a given theme. A fascinating data pointfrom this analysis is that, even though sexual imageryandpatolliboardseachcomprise2.2percentoftheover-allcorpus,thereisavastliteratureonpatolli,whilealmostnothinghasbeensaidabouthowtoreadsexualimagery.ThishandicapsZralka,whoreliesontheinterpretationsofotherscholarsforthesesubjectareas.Theresultisthathis analysis of the remarkably diverse sexual imagerycomes across as puritanical and narrow. Why can timages of vulvas be considered erotic sexual symbols
